[0.019, "o", "node\u001b[?25l\u001b[1;81H only output the code'                                                         \u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[1m\u001b[2;81HThinking...\u001b[m\u000f                                                                    \u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[3;81HPlan:\u001b[39m                                                                          \u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[4;81H1. Define a graph representation (e.g., adjacency list).\u001b[39m                       \u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[5;81H2. Implement the DFS function using recursion or an explicit stack.\u001b[39m            \u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[6;81H3. Apply \"expert\" style: type hinting, clear variable names, efficient \u001b[39m        \u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[7;81Hstructure, and potentially incorporating visited set handling for cycle \u001b[39m       \u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[8;81Hdetection/efficiency.\u001b[39m                                                          \u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[9;81H4. Ensure the output is *only* the code.\u001b[39m                                       \u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[1m\u001b[10;81H...done thinking.\u001b[m\u000f                                                              \u001b[11;81H                                                                               \u001b[12;81H```python                                                                      \u001b[13;81Hfrom typing import Dict, List, Any, Set, Callable, Tuple                       \u001b[14;81H                                                                               \u001b[15;81Hdef depth_first_search(graph: Dict[Any, List[Any]], start_node: Any) ->        \u001b[16;81HSet[Any]:                                                                      \u001b[17;81H    \"\"\"                                                                        \u001b[18;81H    Performs a Depth-First Search (DFS) traversal starting from a              \u001b[19;81Hspecified node.                                                                \u001b[20;81H                                                                               \u001b[21;81H    This implementation utilizes an explicit stack for iterative               \u001b[22;81Htraversal,                                                                     \u001b[23;81H    which is generally preferred over deep recursion for production code       \u001b[24;81H    to prevent potential StackOverflowErrors on large graphs.                  \u001b[25;81H                                                                               \u001b[26;81H    Args:                                                                      \u001b[27;81H        graph: A dictionary representing the graph, where keys are nodes       \u001b[28;81H               and values are lists of neighbors (adjacency list).             \u001b[29;81H        start_node: The node from which the traversal begins.                  \u001b[30;81H                                                                               \u001b[31;81H    Returns:                                                                   \u001b[32;81H        A set containing all unique nodes visited during the traversal.        \u001b[33;81H                                                                               \u001b[34;81H    Raises:                                                                    \u001b[35;81H        ValueError: If the start_node is not present in the graph.             \u001b[36;81H    \"\"\"                                                                        \u001b[37;81H    if start_node not in graph:                                                \u001b[38;81H        raise ValueError(f\"Start node '{start_node}' is not part of the        \u001b[39;81Hprovided graph.\")                                                              \u001b[40;81H                                                                               \u001b[41;81H    # Set to track visited nodes ensures O(1) lookup time and prevents         \u001b[42;81Hcycles from infinite loops.                                                    \u001b[43;81H    visited: Set[Any] = set()                                                  \u001b[44;81H                                                                               \u001b[45;81H    # Stack for iterative DFS traversal. Initialized with the start node.      \u001b[46;81H    stack: List[Any] "]
[0.000, "o", "= [start_node]                                            \u001b[47;81H                                                                               \u001b[48;81H    while stack:                                                               \u001b[49;81H        # Pop the current node to process                                      \u001b[50;81H        current_node: Any = stack.pop()                                        \u001b[51;81H                                                                               \u001b[52;81H        if current_node not in visited:                                        \u001b[53;81H            # 1. Process the node (e.g., print it, add it to results)          \u001b[54;81H            visited.add(current_node)                                          \u001b[55;81H                                                                               \u001b[56;81H            # 2. Add unvisited neighbors to the stack.                         \u001b[57;81H            # Since we pop the stack, adding neighbors in reverse order        \u001b[58;81H            # (or processing the adjacency list in reverse) ensures that       \u001b[59;81H            # the neighbors are processed in the natural order defined by      \u001b[60;81Hthe graph's list.                                                              \u001b[61;81H            # This makes the traversal deterministic when the neighbors        \u001b[62;81Hlist order matters.                                                            \u001b[63;81H            neighbors = graph.get(current_node, [])                            \u001b[64;81H                                                                               \u001b[34h\u001b[?25h\u001b[62;186H"]
[0.049, "o", "\u001b[50;3H\u001b[38;5;245m  **\u001b[62;186H\u001b[39m):\u001b[64;81H            \u001b[62;188H"]
[0.045, "o", "\u001b[?25l\u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[1m\u001b[1;81HThinking...\u001b[m\u000f                                                                    \u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[2;81HPlan:\u001b[39m                                                                          \u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[3;81H1. Define a graph representation (e.g., adjacency list).\u001b[39m                       \u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[4;81H2. Implement the DFS function using recursion or an explicit stack.\u001b[39m            \u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[5;81H3. Apply \"expert\" style: type hinting, clear variable names, efficient \u001b[39m        \u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[6;81Hstructure, and potentially incorporating visited set handling for cycle \u001b[39m       \u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[7;81Hdetection/efficiency.\u001b[39m                                                          \u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[8;81H4. Ensure the output is *only* the code.\u001b[39m                                       \u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[1m\u001b[9;81H...done thinking.\u001b[m\u000f                                                              \u001b[10;81H                                                                               \u001b[11;81H```python                                                                      \u001b[12;81Hfrom typing import Dict, List, Any, Set, Callable, Tuple                       \u001b[13;81H                                                                               \u001b[14;81Hdef depth_first_search(graph: Dict[Any, List[Any]], start_node: Any) ->        \u001b[15;81HSet[Any]:                                                                      \u001b[16;81H    \"\"\"                                                                        \u001b[17;81H    Performs a Depth-First Search (DFS) traversal starting from a              \u001b[18;81Hspecified node.                                                                \u001b[19;81H                                                                               \u001b[20;81H    This implementation utilizes an explicit stack for iterative               \u001b[21;81Htraversal,                                                                     \u001b[22;81H    which is generally preferred over deep recursion for production code       \u001b[23;81H    to prevent potential StackOverflowErrors on large graphs.                  \u001b[24;81H                                                                               \u001b[25;81H    Args:                                                                      \u001b[26;81H        graph: A dictionary representing the graph, where keys are nodes       \u001b[27;81H               and values are lists of neighbors (adjacency list).             \u001b[28;81H        start_node: The node from which the traversal begins.                  \u001b[29;81H                                                                               \u001b[30;81H    Returns:                                                                   \u001b[31;81H        A set containing all unique nodes visited during the traversal.        \u001b[32;81H                                                                               \u001b[33;81H    Raises:                                                                    \u001b[34;81H        ValueError: If the start_node is not present in the graph.             \u001b[35;81H    \"\"\"                                                                        \u001b[36;81H    if start_node not in graph:                                                \u001b[37;81H        raise ValueError(f\"Start node '{start_node}' is not part of the        \u001b[38;81Hprovided graph.\")                                                              \u001b[39;81H                                                                               \u001b[40;81H    # Set to track visited nodes ensures O(1) lookup time and prevents         \u001b[41;81Hcycles from infinite loops.                                                    \u001b[42;81H    visited: Set[Any] = set()                                                  \u001b[43;81H                                                                               \u001b[44;81H    # Stack for iterative DFS traversal. Initialized with the start node.      \u001b[45;81H    stack: List[Any] = [start_node]                                            \u001b[46;81H                         "]
[0.001, "o", "                                                      \u001b[47;81H    while stack:                                                               \u001b[48;81H        # Pop the current node to process                                      \u001b[49;81H        current_node: Any = stack.pop()                                        \u001b[50;81H                                                                               \u001b[51;81H        if current_node not in visited:                                        \u001b[52;81H            # 1. Process the node (e.g., print it, add it to results)          \u001b[53;81H            visited.add(current_node)                                          \u001b[54;81H                                                                               \u001b[55;81H            # 2. Add unvisited neighbors to the stack.                         \u001b[56;81H            # Since we pop the stack, adding neighbors in reverse order        \u001b[57;81H            # (or processing the adjacency list in reverse) ensures that       \u001b[58;81H            # the neighbors are processed in the natural order defined by      \u001b[59;81Hthe graph's list.                                                              \u001b[60;81H            # This makes the traversal deterministic when the neighbors        \u001b[61;81Hlist order matters.                                                            \u001b[62;81H            neighbors = graph.get(current_node, [])                            \u001b[63;81H                                                                               \u001b[64;81H                                                                               \u001b[34h\u001b[?25h\u001b[63;161H\u001b[50;7H\u001b[38;5;245mGenerating\u001b[63;161H\u001b[m\u000f"]
