[0.000, "o", "\u001b[?25l\u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[1d    *   Mark `start_node` as visited.\u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[2;161H    *   Process `start_node` (e.g., print it).\u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[3;161H    *   For each neighbor `v` of `start_node`:\u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[4;161H        *   If `v` is not visited:\u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[5;161H            *   Recursively call `dfs(graph, v, visited)`.\u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[6;161H\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\n7.  **Refining for Compactness (Python):**\u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[8;161H    *   I'll wrap it in a class or a self-contained function, but a \u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[9;161Hfunction is simpler for a compact example.\u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[10;161H    *   I need to handle the graph setup and calling mechanism cleanly.\u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[11;161H\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\n*(Self-Correction/Refinement: To make it compact, I will use a function \u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[13;161Hthat takes the graph and the starting node, and I will use a set for \u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[14;161H`visited` checks.)*\u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[15;161H\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\n8.  **Final Code Structure (Using recursion for maximum compactness):**\u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[17;161H\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\n```python\u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[19;161Hdef dfs(graph, start):\u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[20;161H    visited = set()\u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[21;161H    # Use a stack/list for explicit traversal if avoiding recursion depth \u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[22;161Hlimit,\u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[23;161H    # but recursion is more compact conceptually. Let's stick to \u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[24;161Hrecursion.\u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[25;161H\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\n    def explore(node):\u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[27;161H        if node not in visited:\u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[28;161H            print(node) # Action to perform on visiting\u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[29;161H            visited.add(node)\u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[30;161H            for neighbor in graph.get(node, []):\u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[31;161H                explore(neighbor)\u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[32;161H\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\n    explore(start)\u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[34;161H\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\n# Example usage setup\u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[36;161H# graph = { ... }\u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[37;161H# dfs(graph, 'A')\u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[38;161H```\u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[39;161H\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\n(I will simplify the final output by making it a single self-contained \u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[41;161Hset of functions/logic, demonstrating the core recursive pattern.)\u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[1m\u001b[42;161H...done thinking.\u001b[m\u000f\u001b[K\u001b[43;161H\u001b[K\n```python\u001b[K\u001b[45;161Hdef dfs(graph, start_node):\u001b[K\u001b[46;161H    \"\"\"Performs Depth-First Search on a graph represented by an adjacency \u001b[K\u001b[47;161Hdictionary.\"\"\"\u001b[K\u001b[48;161H    visited = set()\u001b[K\u001b[49;161H\u001b[K\n    def explore(node):\u001b[K\u001b[51;161H        if node not in visited:\u001b[K\u001b[52;161H            # Action upon visiting the node (e.g., printing it)\u001b[K\u001b[53;161H            print(node)\u001b[K\u001b[54;161H            visited.add(node)\u001b[K\u001b[55;161H\u001b[K\n            # Recursively call DFS for all unvisited neighbors\u001b[K\u001b[57;161H            for neighbor in graph.get(node, []):\u001b[K\u001b[58;161H                explore(neighbor)\u001b[K\u001b[59;161H\u001b[K\n    explore(start_node)\u001b[K\u001b[61;161H\u001b[K\n# Example Usage:\u001b[K\u001b[63;161H# Graph defined as an adjacency dictionary\u001b[K\u001b[64;161H\u001b[K\u001b[34h\u001b[?25h"]
