[0.000, "o", "\u001b[?25l\u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[1d    *   For each neighbor `v` of `start_node`:\u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[2;161H        *   If `v` is not visited:\u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[3;161H            *   Recursively call `dfs(graph, v, visited)`.\u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[4;161H\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\n7.  **Refining for Compactness (Python):**\u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[6;161H    *   I'll wrap it in a class or a self-contained function, but a \u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[7;161Hfunction is simpler for a compact example.\u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[8;161H    *   I need to handle the graph setup and calling mechanism cleanly.\u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[9;161H\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\n*(Self-Correction/Refinement: To make it compact, I will use a function \u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[11;161Hthat takes the graph and the starting node, and I will use a set for \u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[12;161H`visited` checks.)*\u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[13;161H\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\n8.  **Final Code Structure (Using recursion for maximum compactness):**\u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[15;161H\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\n```python\u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[17;161Hdef dfs(graph, start):\u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[18;161H    visited = set()\u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[19;161H    # Use a stack/list for explicit traversal if avoiding recursion depth \u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[20;161Hlimit,\u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[21;161H    # but recursion is more compact conceptually. Let's stick to \u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[22;161Hrecursion.\u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[23;161H\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\n    def explore(node):\u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[25;161H        if node not in visited:\u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[26;161H            print(node) # Action to perform on visiting\u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[27;161H            visited.add(node)\u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[28;161H            for neighbor in graph.get(node, []):\u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[29;161H                explore(neighbor)\u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[30;161H\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\n    explore(start)\u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[32;161H\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\n# Example usage setup\u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[34;161H# graph = { ... }\u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[35;161H# dfs(graph, 'A')\u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[36;161H```\u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[37;161H\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\n(I will simplify the final output by making it a single self-contained \u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[39;161Hset of functions/logic, demonstrating the core recursive pattern.)\u001b[39m\u001b[K\u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[1m\u001b[40;161H...done thinking.\u001b[m\u000f\u001b[K\u001b[41;161H\u001b[K\n```python\u001b[K\u001b[43;161Hdef dfs(graph, start_node):\u001b[K\u001b[44;161H    \"\"\"Performs Depth-First Search on a graph represented by an adjacency \u001b[K\u001b[45;161Hdictionary.\"\"\"\u001b[K\u001b[46;161H    visited = set()\u001b[K\u001b[47;161H\u001b[K\n    def explore(node):\u001b[K\u001b[49;161H        if node not in visited:\u001b[K\u001b[50;161H            # Action upon visiting the node (e.g., printing it)\u001b[K\u001b[51;161H            print(node)\u001b[K\u001b[52;161H            visited.add(node)\u001b[K\u001b[53;161H\u001b[K\n            # Recursively call DFS for all unvisited neighbors\u001b[K\u001b[55;161H            for neighbor in graph.get(node, []):\u001b[K\u001b[56;161H                explore(neighbor)\u001b[K\u001b[57;161H\u001b[K\n    explore(start_node)\u001b[K\u001b[59;161H\u001b[K\n# Example Usage:\u001b[K\u001b[61;161H# Graph defined as an adjacency dictionary\u001b[K\u001b[62;161Hgraph = {\u001b[K\u001b[63;161H    'A': ['B', 'C'],\u001b[K\u001b[64;161H\u001b[K\u001b[34h\u001b[?25h"]
[0.052, "o", "\u001b[71DE\u001b[70C\u001b[?25l\u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[H1.  **Goal:** Write a Depth-First Search (DFS) implementation in Python.\u001b[39m       \u001b[38;5;245m\r\n2.  **Constraint/Style:** Beginner level. This means the code should be \u001b[39m       \u001b[38;5;245m\r\nclear, heavily commented (or structured to be easily understood by a \u001b[39m          \u001b[38;5;245m\r\nbeginner), and use simple, standard techniques (like recursion or an \u001b[39m          \u001b[5;79H\u001b[1K\u001b[38;5;245m\rexplicit stack).\u001b[39m\u001b[6;79H\u001b[1K\u001b[38;5;245m\r3.  **Output:** Only the code.\u001b[39m\u001b[7;79H\u001b[1K\n\u001b[1K\u001b[38;5;245m\r4.  **Choosing the Data Structure:**\r\n    *   DFS is naturally implemented using a Stack (LIFO).\u001b[39m                     \u001b[38;5;245m\r\n    *   In Python, recursion implicitly uses the call stack, which is \u001b[39m         \u001b[38;5;245m\r\noften the *most* beginner-friendly way to teach DFS first.\u001b[39m                     \u001b[38;5;245m\r\n    *   I will provide the *recursive* approach, as it's the most \u001b[39m             \u001b[38;5;245m\r\nPythonic and easiest for a beginner to grasp the concept.\u001b[39m                      \u001b[14;79H\u001b[1K\u001b[38;5;245m\r\n5.  **Designing the Graph Representation:**\u001b[39m                                    \u001b[38;5;245m\r\n    *   A dictionary where keys are nodes and values are lists of \u001b[39m             \u001b[38;5;245m\r\nneighbors is the standard, easiest way for beginner graph problems.\u001b[39m            \u001b[38;5;245m\r\n    *   *Example:* `graph = {'A': ['B', 'C'], 'B': ['D'], ...}`\u001b[39m                \u001b[19;79H\u001b[1K\u001b[38;5;245m\r\n6.  **Implementing the DFS Logic (Recursive Approach):**\u001b[39m                       \u001b[38;5;245m\r\n    *   Need a function `dfs(start_node, visited_set, graph)`.\u001b[39m                 \u001b[38;5;245m\r\n    *   *Base Case/Check:* Before processing a node, check if it has \u001b[39m          \u001b[38;5;245m\r\nalready been visited. If so, return immediately.\u001b[39m                               \u001b[38;5;245m\r\n    *   *Action:* Mark the current node as visited (add it to the \u001b[39m             \u001b[38;5;245m\r\n`visited_set`) and process it (e.g., print it).\u001b[39m                                \u001b[38;5;245m\r\n    *   *Recursive Step:* Iterate through all neighbors of the current \u001b[39m        \u001b[38;5;245m\r\nnode. For each neighbor, call `dfs()` recursively on that neighbor.\u001b[39m            \u001b[28;79H\u001b[1K\u001b[38;5;245m\r\n7.  **Refinement (Beginner Style Focus):**\u001b[39m                                     \u001b[38;5;245m\r\n    *   I need to make the function signature clean and the overall \u001b[39m           \u001b[31;79H\u001b[1K\u001b[38;5;245m\rstructure runnable.\r\n    *   I must include comments explaining *why* the code works, \u001b[39m              \u001b[38;5;245m\r\nespecially the role of the `visited` set.\u001b[39m                                      \u001b[34;79H\u001b[1K\u001b[38;5;245m\r\n8.  **Final Code Structure (Self-Correction/Review):**\u001b[39m                         \u001b[36;79H\u001b[1K\u001b[38;5;245m\r    *   Define the graph.\r\n    *   Define the main `dfs` helper function.\u001b[39m                                 \u001b[38;5;245m\r\n    *   Define a wrapper function (or simply call the helper) to initiate \u001b[39m     \u001b[39;79H\u001b[1K\u001b[38;5;245m\rthe search.\u001b[39m\u001b[40;79H\u001b[1K\u001b[38;5;245m\r\n*(Self-Correction during implementation: Ensure the graph handles \u001b[39m             \u001b[38;5;245m\r\npotential unconnected components, although for simplicity, a single entry \u001b[39m     \u001b[38;5;245m\r\npoint `dfs(start_node)` is sufficient for the initial version.)*\u001b[39m               \u001b[44;79H\u001b[1K\u001b[38;5;245m\r\n9.  **Generating the final output (The resulting code block).**\u001b[39m                \u001b[46;79H\u001b[1K\u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[1m\r...done thinking.\u001b[m\u000f\u001b[47;79H\u001b[1K\n\u001b[1K\r```python\r\n# Graph representation using an adjacency dictionary                           \u001b[50;79H\u001b[1K\r# Key = Node, Value = List of neighbors\u001b[51;79H\u001b[1K\rgraph = {\u001b[52;79H\u001b[1K\r    'A': ['B', 'C'],\u001b[53;79H\u001b[1K\r    'B': ['D', 'E'],\u001b[54;79H\u001b[1K\r    'C': ['F'],\u001b[55;79H\u001b[1K\r    'D': ['F'],\r\n    'E': ['A', 'F'], # Note: Creating a cycle to show robustness               \u001b[57;79H\u001b[1K\r    'F': []\u001b[58;79H\u001b[1K\r}\u001b[59;79H\u001b[1K\n\u001b[1K\rdef depth_first_search(start_node):\u001b[61;79H\u001b[1K\r    \"\"\"\r\n    Performs Depth-First Search (DFS) starting from a given node.              \u001b[63;79H\u001b["]
