[0.001, "o", "\u001b[?25l\u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[Hclear, heavily commented (or structured to be easily understood by a \u001b[39m          \u001b[38;5;245m\r\nbeginner), and use simple, standard techniques (like recursion or an \u001b[39m          \u001b[3;79H\u001b[1K\u001b[38;5;245m\rexplicit stack).\u001b[39m\u001b[4;79H\u001b[1K\u001b[38;5;245m\r3.  **Output:** Only the code.\u001b[39m\u001b[5;79H\u001b[1K\n\u001b[1K\u001b[38;5;245m\r4.  **Choosing the Data Structure:**\r\n    *   DFS is naturally implemented using a Stack (LIFO).\u001b[39m                     \u001b[38;5;245m\r\n    *   In Python, recursion implicitly uses the call stack, which is \u001b[39m         \u001b[38;5;245m\r\noften the *most* beginner-friendly way to teach DFS first.\u001b[39m                     \u001b[38;5;245m\r\n    *   I will provide the *recursive* approach, as it's the most \u001b[39m             \u001b[38;5;245m\r\nPythonic and easiest for a beginner to grasp the concept.\u001b[39m                      \u001b[12;79H\u001b[1K\u001b[38;5;245m\r\n5.  **Designing the Graph Representation:**\u001b[39m                                    \u001b[38;5;245m\r\n    *   A dictionary where keys are nodes and values are lists of \u001b[39m             \u001b[38;5;245m\r\nneighbors is the standard, easiest way for beginner graph problems.\u001b[39m            \u001b[38;5;245m\r\n    *   *Example:* `graph = {'A': ['B', 'C'], 'B': ['D'], ...}`\u001b[39m                \u001b[17;79H\u001b[1K\u001b[38;5;245m\r\n6.  **Implementing the DFS Logic (Recursive Approach):**\u001b[39m                       \u001b[38;5;245m\r\n    *   Need a function `dfs(start_node, visited_set, graph)`.\u001b[39m                 \u001b[38;5;245m\r\n    *   *Base Case/Check:* Before processing a node, check if it has \u001b[39m          \u001b[38;5;245m\r\nalready been visited. If so, return immediately.\u001b[39m                               \u001b[38;5;245m\r\n    *   *Action:* Mark the current node as visited (add it to the \u001b[39m             \u001b[38;5;245m\r\n`visited_set`) and process it (e.g., print it).\u001b[39m                                \u001b[38;5;245m\r\n    *   *Recursive Step:* Iterate through all neighbors of the current \u001b[39m        \u001b[38;5;245m\r\nnode. For each neighbor, call `dfs()` recursively on that neighbor.\u001b[39m            \u001b[26;79H\u001b[1K\u001b[38;5;245m\r\n7.  **Refinement (Beginner Style Focus):**\u001b[39m                                     \u001b[38;5;245m\r\n    *   I need to make the function signature clean and the overall \u001b[39m           \u001b[29;79H\u001b[1K\u001b[38;5;245m\rstructure runnable.\r\n    *   I must include comments explaining *why* the code works, \u001b[39m              \u001b[38;5;245m\r\nespecially the role of the `visited` set.\u001b[39m                                      \u001b[32;79H\u001b[1K\u001b[38;5;245m\r\n8.  **Final Code Structure (Self-Correction/Review):**\u001b[39m                         \u001b[34;79H\u001b[1K\u001b[38;5;245m\r    *   Define the graph.\r\n    *   Define the main `dfs` helper function.\u001b[39m                                 \u001b[38;5;245m\r\n    *   Define a wrapper function (or simply call the helper) to initiate \u001b[39m     \u001b[37;79H\u001b[1K\u001b[38;5;245m\rthe search.\u001b[39m\u001b[38;79H\u001b[1K\u001b[38;5;245m\r\n*(Self-Correction during implementation: Ensure the graph handles \u001b[39m             \u001b[38;5;245m\r\npotential unconnected components, although for simplicity, a single entry \u001b[39m     \u001b[38;5;245m\r\npoint `dfs(start_node)` is sufficient for the initial version.)*\u001b[39m               \u001b[42;79H\u001b[1K\u001b[38;5;245m\r\n9.  **Generating the final output (The resulting code block).**\u001b[39m                \u001b[44;79H\u001b[1K\u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[1m\r...done thinking.\u001b[m\u000f\u001b[45;79H\u001b[1K\n\u001b[1K\r```python\r\n# Graph representation using an adjacency dictionary                           \u001b[48;79H\u001b[1K\r# Key = Node, Value = List of neighbors\u001b[49;79H\u001b[1K\rgraph = {\u001b[50;79H\u001b[1K\r    'A': ['B', 'C'],\u001b[51;79H\u001b[1K\r    'B': ['D', 'E'],\u001b[52;79H\u001b[1K\r    'C': ['F'],\u001b[53;79H\u001b[1K\r    'D': ['F'],\r\n    'E': ['A', 'F'], # Note: Creating a cycle to show robustness               \u001b[55;79H\u001b[1K\r    'F': []\u001b[56;79H\u001b[1K\r}\u001b[57;79H\u001b[1K\n\u001b[1K\rdef depth_first_search(start_node):\u001b[59;79H\u001b[1K\r    \"\"\"\r\n    Performs Depth-First Search (DFS) starting from a given node.              \u001b[61;79H\u001b[1K\r    \r\n    DFS explores as far as possible along each branch before                   \u001b[63;79H\u001b[1K\rbacktracking.\u001b[64;79H\u001b[1K\u001b[1;81H    This implementation utilizes an explicit stack for iterative        "]
[0.000, "o", "       \u001b[2;81Htraversal,                                                                     \u001b[3;81H    which is generally preferred over deep recursion for production code       \u001b[4;81H    to prevent potential StackOverflowErrors on large graphs.                  \u001b[5;81H                                                                               \u001b[6;81H    Args:                                                                      \u001b[7;81H        graph: A dictionary representing the graph, where keys are nodes       \u001b[8;81H               and values are lists of neighbors (adjacency list).             \u001b[9;81H        start_node: The node from which the traversal begins.                  \u001b[10;81H                                                                               \u001b[11;81H    Returns:                                                                   \u001b[12;81H        A set containing all unique nodes visited during the traversal.        \u001b[13;81H                                                                               \u001b[14;81H    Raises:                                                                    \u001b[15;81H        ValueError: If the start_node is not present in the graph.             \u001b[16;81H    \"\"\"                                                                        \u001b[17;81H    if start_node not in graph:                                                \u001b[18;81H        raise ValueError(f\"Start node '{start_node}' is not part of the        \u001b[19;81Hprovided graph.\")                                                              \u001b[20;81H                                                                               \u001b[21;81H    # Set to track visited nodes ensures O(1) lookup time and prevents         \u001b[22;81Hcycles from infinite loops.                                                    \u001b[23;81H    visited: Set[Any] = set()                                                  \u001b[24;81H                                                                               \u001b[25;81H    # Stack for iterative DFS traversal. Initialized with the start node.      \u001b[26;81H    stack: List[Any] = [start_node]                                            \u001b[27;81H                                                                               \u001b[28;81H    while stack:                                                               \u001b[29;81H        # Pop the current node to process                                      \u001b[30;81H        current_node: Any = stack.pop()                                        \u001b[31;81H                                                                               \u001b[32;81H        if current_node not in visited:                                        \u001b[33;81H            # 1. Process the node (e.g., print it, add it to results)          \u001b[34;81H            visited.add(current_node)                                          \u001b[35;81H                                                                               \u001b[36;81H            # 2. Add unvisited neighbors to the stack.                         \u001b[37;81H            # Since we pop the stack, adding neighbors in reverse order        \u001b[38;81H            # (or processing the adjacency list in reverse) ensures that       \u001b[39;81H            # the neighbors are processed in the natural order defined by      \u001b[40;81Hthe graph's list.                                                              \u001b[41;81H            # This makes the traversal deterministic when the neighbors        \u001b[42;81Hlist order matters.                                                            \u001b[43;81H            neighbors = graph.get(current_node, [])                            \u001b[44;81H                                                                               \u001b[45;81H            # Iterate in reverse to maintain canonical traversal order         \u001b[46;81H(e.g., A -> B -> C)                                                            \u001b[47;81H            for neighbor in reversed(neighbors):                               \u001b[48;81H                if neighbor not in visited:                                    \u001b[49;81"]
[0.000, "o", "H                    stack.append(neighbor)                                     \u001b[50;81H                                                                               \u001b[51;81H    return visited                                                             \u001b[52;81H                                                                               \u001b[53;81H# --- Example Usage ---                                                        \u001b[54;81Hif __name__ == '__main__':                                                     \u001b[55;81H    # Example 1: Simple Graph (Adjacency List)                                 \u001b[56;81H    graph1: Dict[str, List[str]] = {                                           \u001b[57;81H        \"A\": [\"B\", \"C\"],                                                       \u001b[58;81H        \"B\": [\"D\", \"E\"],                                                       \u001b[59;81H        \"C\": [\"F\"],                                                            \u001b[60;81H        \"D\": [\"E\"],                                                            \u001b[61;81H        \"E\": [\"F\"],                                                            \u001b[62;81H        \"F\": []                                                                \u001b[63;81H    }                                                                          \u001b[64;81H                                                                               \u001b[34h\u001b[?25h\u001b[9C"]
