[0.002, "o", "\u001b[?25l\u001b[1;79H\u001b[1K\n\u001b[1K\u001b[38;5;245m\r4.  **Choosing the Data Structure:**\r\n    *   DFS is naturally implemented using a Stack (LIFO).\u001b[39m                     \u001b[38;5;245m\r\n    *   In Python, recursion implicitly uses the call stack, which is \u001b[39m         \u001b[38;5;245m\r\noften the *most* beginner-friendly way to teach DFS first.\u001b[39m                     \u001b[38;5;245m\r\n    *   I will provide the *recursive* approach, as it's the most \u001b[39m             \u001b[38;5;245m\r\nPythonic and easiest for a beginner to grasp the concept.\u001b[39m                      \u001b[8;79H\u001b[1K\u001b[38;5;245m\r\n5.  **Designing the Graph Representation:**\u001b[39m                                    \u001b[38;5;245m\r\n    *   A dictionary where keys are nodes and values are lists of \u001b[39m             \u001b[38;5;245m\r\nneighbors is the standard, easiest way for beginner graph problems.\u001b[39m            \u001b[38;5;245m\r\n    *   *Example:* `graph = {'A': ['B', 'C'], 'B': ['D'], ...}`\u001b[39m                \u001b[13;79H\u001b[1K\u001b[38;5;245m\r\n6.  **Implementing the DFS Logic (Recursive Approach):**\u001b[39m                       \u001b[38;5;245m\r\n    *   Need a function `dfs(start_node, visited_set, graph)`.\u001b[39m                 \u001b[38;5;245m\r\n    *   *Base Case/Check:* Before processing a node, check if it has \u001b[39m          \u001b[38;5;245m\r\nalready been visited. If so, return immediately.\u001b[39m                               \u001b[38;5;245m\r\n    *   *Action:* Mark the current node as visited (add it to the \u001b[39m             \u001b[38;5;245m\r\n`visited_set`) and process it (e.g., print it).\u001b[39m                                \u001b[38;5;245m\r\n    *   *Recursive Step:* Iterate through all neighbors of the current \u001b[39m        \u001b[38;5;245m\r\nnode. For each neighbor, call `dfs()` recursively on that neighbor.\u001b[39m            \u001b[22;79H\u001b[1K\u001b[38;5;245m\r\n7.  **Refinement (Beginner Style Focus):**\u001b[39m                                     \u001b[38;5;245m\r\n    *   I need to make the function signature clean and the overall \u001b[39m           \u001b[25;79H\u001b[1K\u001b[38;5;245m\rstructure runnable.\r\n    *   I must include comments explaining *why* the code works, \u001b[39m              \u001b[38;5;245m\r\nespecially the role of the `visited` set.\u001b[39m                                      \u001b[28;79H\u001b[1K\u001b[38;5;245m\r\n8.  **Final Code Structure (Self-Correction/Review):**\u001b[39m                         \u001b[30;79H\u001b[1K\u001b[38;5;245m\r    *   Define the graph.\r\n    *   Define the main `dfs` helper function.\u001b[39m                                 \u001b[38;5;245m\r\n    *   Define a wrapper function (or simply call the helper) to initiate \u001b[39m     \u001b[33;79H\u001b[1K\u001b[38;5;245m\rthe search.\u001b[39m\u001b[34;79H\u001b[1K\u001b[38;5;245m\r\n*(Self-Correction during implementation: Ensure the graph handles \u001b[39m             \u001b[38;5;245m\r\npotential unconnected components, although for simplicity, a single entry \u001b[39m     \u001b[38;5;245m\r\npoint `dfs(start_node)` is sufficient for the initial version.)*\u001b[39m               \u001b[38;79H\u001b[1K\u001b[38;5;245m\r\n9.  **Generating the final output (The resulting code block).**\u001b[39m                \u001b[40;79H\u001b[1K\u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[1m\r...done thinking.\u001b[m\u000f\u001b[41;79H\u001b[1K\n\u001b[1K\r```python\r\n# Graph representation using an adjacency dictionary                           \u001b[44;79H\u001b[1K\r# Key = Node, Value = List of neighbors\u001b[45;79H\u001b[1K\rgraph = {\u001b[46;79H\u001b[1K\r    'A': ['B', 'C'],\u001b[47;79H\u001b[1K\r    'B': ['D', 'E'],\u001b[48;79H\u001b[1K\r    'C': ['F'],\u001b[49;79H\u001b[1K\r    'D': ['F'],\r\n    'E': ['A', 'F'], # Note: Creating a cycle to show robustness               \u001b[51;79H\u001b[1K\r    'F': []\u001b[52;79H\u001b[1K\r}\u001b[53;79H\u001b[1K\n\u001b[1K\rdef depth_first_search(start_node):\u001b[55;79H\u001b[1K\r    \"\"\"\r\n    Performs Depth-First Search (DFS) starting from a given node.              \u001b[57;79H\u001b[1K\r    \r\n    DFS explores as far as possible along each branch before                   \u001b[59;79H\u001b[1K\rbacktracking.\u001b[60;79H\u001b[1K\r    \"\"\"\u001b[61;79H\u001b[1K\r    \r\n    # 1. visited set: This is crucial! It prevents us from going into          \r\n    #    an infinite loop if the graph contains cycles (e.g., A -> B ->        \u001b[64;79H\u001b[1K\rA).\u001b[34h\u001b[?25h\u001b[159C"]
