;5;245m\r\npotential unconnected components, although for simplicity, a single entry \u001b[39m     \u001b[38;5;245m\r\npoint `dfs(start_node)` is sufficient for the initial version.)*\u001b[39m               \u001b[25;79H\u001b[1K\u001b[38;5;245m\r\n9.  **Generating the final output (The resulting code block).**\u001b[39m                \u001b[27;79H\u001b[1K\u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[1m\r...done thinking.\u001b[m\u000f\u001b[28;79H\u001b[1K\n\u001b[1K\r```python\r\n# Graph representation using an adjacency dictionary                           \u001b[31;79H\u001b[1K\r# Key = Node, Value = List of neighbors\u001b[32;79H\u001b[1K\rgraph = {\u001b[33;79H\u001b[1K\r    'A': ['B', 'C'],\u001b[34;79H\u001b[1K\r    'B': ['D', 'E'],\u001b[35;79H\u001b[1K\r    'C': ['F'],\u001b[36;79H\u001b[1K\r    'D': ['F'],\r\n    'E': ['A', 'F'], # Note: Creating a cycle to show robustness               \u001b[38;79H\u001b[1K\r    'F': []\u001b[39;79H\u001b[1K\r}\u001b[40;79H\u001b[1K\n\u001b[1K\rdef depth_first_search(start_node):\u001b[42;79H\u001b[1K\r    \"\"\"\r\n    Performs Depth-First Search (DFS) starting from a given node.              \u001b[44;79H\u001b[1K\r    \r\n    DFS explores as far as possible along each branch before                   \u001b[46;79H\u001b[1K\rbacktracking.\u001b[47;79H\u001b[1K\r    \"\"\"\u001b[48;79H\u001b[1K\r    \r\n    # 1. visited set: This is crucial! It prevents us from going into          \r\n    #    an infinite loop if the graph contains cycles (e.g., A -> B ->        \u001b[51;79H\u001b[1K\rA).\u001b[52;79H\u001b[1K\r    visited = set()\u001b[53;79H\u001b[1K\r    \r\n    # The actual recursive helper function                                     \u001b[55;79H\u001b[1K\r    def dfs_recursive(node):\r\n        # Step 1: Check if we've already processed this node                   \u001b[57;79H\u001b[1K\r        if node in visited:\r\n            return # If visited, stop this path                                \u001b[59;79H\u001b[1K\r        \r\