[0.001, "o", "\u001b[?25l\u001b[1;79H\u001b[1K\u001b[38;5;245m\r\n8.  **Final Code Structure (Self-Correction/Review):**\u001b[39m                         \u001b[3;79H\u001b[1K\u001b[38;5;245m\r    *   Define the graph.\r\n    *   Define the main `dfs` helper function.\u001b[39m                                 \u001b[38;5;245m\r\n    *   Define a wrapper function (or simply call the helper) to initiate \u001b[39m     \u001b[6;79H\u001b[1K\u001b[38;5;245m\rthe search.\u001b[39m\u001b[7;79H\u001b[1K\u001b[38;5;245m\r\n*(Self-Correction during implementation: Ensure the graph handles \u001b[39m             \u001b[38;5;245m\r\npotential unconnected components, although for simplicity, a single entry \u001b[39m     \u001b[38;5;245m\r\npoint `dfs(start_node)` is sufficient for the initial version.)*\u001b[39m               \u001b[11;79H\u001b[1K\u001b[38;5;245m\r\n9.  **Generating the final output (The resulting code block).**\u001b[39m                \u001b[13;79H\u001b[1K\u001b[38;5;245m\u001b[1m\r...done thinking.\u001b[m\u000f\u001b[14;79H\u001b[1K\n\u001b[1K\r```python\r\n# Graph representation using an adjacency dictionary                           \u001b[17;79H\u001b[1K\r# Key = Node, Value = List of neighbors\u001b[18;79H\u001b[1K\rgraph = {\u001b[19;79H\u001b[1K\r    'A': ['B', 'C'],\u001b[20;79H\u001b[1K\r    'B': ['D', 'E'],\u001b[21;79H\u001b[1K\r    'C': ['F'],\u001b[22;79H\u001b[1K\r    'D': ['F'],\r\n    'E': ['A', 'F'], # Note: Creating a cycle to show robustness               \u001b[24;79H\u001b[1K\r    'F': []\u001b[25;79H\u001b[1K\r}\u001b[26;79H\u001b[1K\n\u001b[1K\rdef depth_first_search(start_node):\u001b[28;79H\u001b[1K\r    \"\"\"\r\n    Performs Depth-First Search (DFS) starting from a given node.              \u001b[30;79H\u001b[1K\r    \r\n    DFS explores as far as possible along each branch before                   \u001b[32;79H\u001b[1K\rbacktracking.\u001b[33;79H\u001b[1K\r    \"\"\"\u001b[34;79H\u001b[1K\r    \r\n    # 1. visited set: This is crucial! It prevents us from going into          \r\n    #    an infinite loop if the graph contains cycles (e.g., A -> B ->        \u001b[37;79H\u001b[1K\rA).\u001b[38;79H\u001b[1K\r    visited = set()\u001b[39;79H\u001b[1K\r    \r\n    # The actual recursive helper function                                     \u001b[41;79H\u001b[1K\r    def dfs_recursive(node):\r\n        # Step 1: Check if we've already processed this node                   \u001b[43;79H\u001b[1K\r        if node in visited:\r\n            return # If visited, stop this path                                \u001b[45;79H\u001b[1K\r        \r\n        # Step 2: Process the current node (Mark it and print it)              \u001b[47;79H\u001b[1K\r        visited.add(node)\r\n        print(node, end=\" \") # Display the node being visited                  \u001b[49;79H\u001b[1K\r        \r\n        # Step 3: Explore neighbors (The 'Depth' part)                         \r\n        # For every neighbor of the current node, call the function            \u001b[52;79H\u001b[1K\rrecursively\u001b[53;79H\u001b[1K\r        for neighbor in graph[node]:\r\n            dfs_recursive(neighbor) # This call dives deeper into the          \u001b[55;79H\u001b[1K\rgraph\u001b[56;79H\u001b[1K\r            \u001b[57;79H\u001b[1K\r    # Start the search process\r\n    print(f\"Starting DFS from node {start_node}:\")                             \u001b[59;79H\u001b[1K\r    dfs_recursive(start_node)\u001b[60;79H\u001b[1K\n\u001b[1K\r# --- Execution ---\u001b[62;79H\u001b[1K\n\u001b[1K\r# Start the search from node 'A'\u001b[64;79H\u001b[1K\u001b[34h\u001b[?25h\u001b[84C"]
